Here are some fun facts about Toyota that people may not know:
Toyota was originally founded as a division of the textile company Toyoda Automatic Loom Works in 1937.
Toyota's first passenger car, the Toyota AA, was introduced in 1936. It was Japan's first car with a production volume of 100 units.
The Toyota Corolla is the best-selling car model in history, with over 44 million sold worldwide as of 2021.
Toyota's luxury division, Lexus, was launched in 1989 and quickly gained a reputation for quality and reliability.
Toyota's innovative hybrid technology, which combines a gasoline engine with an electric motor, was first introduced in the Prius in 1997.
The Toyota Production System, which emphasizes continuous improvement and waste reduction, has become a model for manufacturing efficiency and is taught in business schools around the world.
Toyota is the world's largest automaker by volume, with over 10 million vehicles sold annually as of 2021.
Toyota has a long history of involvement in motorsports, including Formula One, NASCAR, and the World Rally Championship.
Toyota has a strong commitment to sustainability, with a goal of achieving net zero carbon emissions by 2050.
Toyota has a strong corporate culture that emphasizes teamwork, respect for others, and a commitment to continuous improvement. This culture is known as the "Toyota Way" and has been emulated by many other companies.
